#Compilation steps
#1 - C# source code
    plain text .cs files — what you write

#2 - Roslyn (compiler)
    job:
        reads .cs files
        checks syntax errors — missing ; {} wrong keywords
        checks semantic errors — wrong types, missing methods
        if no errors → produces a .dll file containing CIL instructions
    features:
        runs live as you type in VSCode
        CIL is the OUTPUT of Roslyn, not a separate step

#3 - CLR (Common Language Runtime)
    job:
        takes the .dll — (Dynamic Link Library)
        JIT (Just-In-Time) compiles CIL into real machine code at runtime
    features:
        memory management
        garbage collection
        security checks
        exception handling

#4 - Machine code
    native instructions your CPU executes
    works on Windows, Linux, Mac
#End
